<LEADPARA>  Final population figures for some areas released by the Census Bureau on
Wednesday prompted renewed charges by officials in several cities that the
1990 census had missed thousands of their residents.;    "It's a serious,
serious undercount," said Susan Weed, Chicago's assistant commissioner for
planning.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BIG CITIES CRITICIZE FINAL CENSUS DATA AS
SERIOUSLY SHORT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Associated Press contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Census Bureau reported Chicago's population at 2.78 million, more than
140,000 short of the figure the city submitted last fall in an official
challenge. While the final figure represented a gain of about 58,000 over
preliminary numbers released in late summer, Weed said the city was not
satisfied with the final count, which could mean a loss of millions of federal
dollars.;    Census Bureau defends data;  Barbara Everitt Bryant, director of
the Census Bureau, has defended the quality of the 1990 census, saying the
Census Bureau figures have in most cases proven to be more accurate than those
from the cities.;    Wednesday's population figures -- for counties, towns and
cities in 18 states and the District of Columbia -- are part of the continuing
release of data from the 1990 census, which was conducted last spring. Figures
for the remaining states are scheduled to be released today and Friday.;
Figures were released Wednesday for Arizona, Arkansas, Delaware, the District
of Columbia, Georgia, Illinois, Indiana, Kansas, Louisiana, Maryland,
Massachusetts, Mississippi, Oklahoma, Rhode Island, South Dakota, Vermont,
Virginia, Washington and West Virginia.;    Flak from big cities;  While
thousands of local jurisdictions had challenged the preliminary findings, it
was the big cities that were most critical of the 1990 census. Even before the
census was conducted, New York, Chicago, Houston and other communities filed a
suit to force the federal government to compensate for residents missed in the
head count by using a statistical formula to arrive at new population
figures.;    As a result of that suit, the government agreed to consider such
an adjustment, and a decision will be announced by July 15.;    In the
meantime, complaints from cities grew even louder Wednesday, when officials
saw that their population counts fell short of the figures they believe are
more accurate.;    Boston's complaint;  "It's embarrassing for the government
to put forward this as a final piece of work," said Allan Stern, a city
official in Boston responsible for the census.;    While city officials
believe Boston's population is more than 600,000, the Census Bureau published
a final count of 574,283, a gain of 20,571 over the preliminary number.;
The statistics hold special significance in Massachusetts, which lost a
congressional seat in the 1990 reapportionment based on its population.;
"We're losing a seat by 12,000 human beings," Stern said. "They're off by more
than twice that in this city alone.";    Atlanta sued;  In Atlanta, where city
officials filed a separate lawsuit in December challenging the census numbers,
the city's final figure prompted similar dismay.;    The Census Bureau's
figure for Atlanta was 394,017, a gain of 9,864 over the preliminary number.;
  "The feeling is those figures are wrong," said Lyn May, a spokeswoman for
Mayor Maynard Jackson. She said the city would pursue its lawsuit.;    The
city believes its population is 437,000. "We stand by those numbers," May
said.;    This is the first time the Census Bureau has released detailed
population figures for the whole nation this early in the census reporting
process. Normally, population counts for localities are released one state at
a time over a period of many months.  </TEXT>
