<HEAD>Count Criticized by States, Cities That Could Lose Federal Bucks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 16th graf ``Ralph Munro'' to fix Munro spelling</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Census Bureau's day-old population count
came under swift criticism Thursday from a key congressman and some
state and local officials who argued it had missed many urban
Americans and would cost large cities federal funds.
   The Bush administration official in charge of the census,
Michael Darby, defended it as ``full, fair and accurate.''
   Rep. Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio, chairman of the House census
subcommittee, said the ppulation count ``may be the first one to
be less accurate than its predecessor.'' He noted the total was 4.7
million people below an estimate made in October, and added,
``We're saying the apparent discrepancy is cause for concern.''
   The count released on Wednesday pegged population in the United
States - excluding nearly 1 million Americans living abroad - at
248.7 million, an increase of nearly 10 percent from a decade ago.
In general, it showed large population gains in California,
Arizona, Florida and other Sun Belt states, and far smaller
increases in the industrial northern states and the agricultural
heartland.
   The governor of New York and the mayor of Meridian, Miss.,
called separately for continued legal challenges to the count. The
census process has been criticized throughout the year by municipal
and state officials, who say it skips people in urban areas,
particularly the poor.
   The census numbers are important to those officials because they
determine how many representatives each state sends to Congress and
how much federal aid states, counties and cities will get. An area
that's undercounted, for example, will have less political clout
and will get less federal money.
   ``New York will continue to make every effort both in the courts
and elsewhere to have all New Yorkers counted, so that we can
maintain our vital and important voice in Washington and ensure our
fair share of federal dollars,'' said New York Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   ``We know where those 5 million folks are,'' Jimmy Kemp, mayor
of Meridian, Miss., said of the difference between the October
estimate and this week's count. ``You're going to find them in your
cities where you have the most economically disadvantaged folks.''
   Rep. Thomas Ridge, R-Pa. and senior Republican on the census and
population subcommittee, said it was wrong to call the difference
between the October ``guesstimate'' and this week's count a
discrepancy.
   ``The fact that you couldn't hit the projection, in my view, is
not legitimate grounds for criticizing the enumeration process
itself,'' Ridge said.
   The Census Bureau said this week that there were in fact 249.6
million Americans. But it isn't accurate to compare that figure to
the 1980 tally because it includes 1 million Americans living
abroad, who weren't counted ten years earlier.
   Darby, the under secretary of commerce in charge of the Census
Bureau, said he believed the 1990 census was ``full, fair and
accurate,'' but he added no one now can say how accurate.
   ``Right now we don't know just how good the census is'' and
won't know until statistical checks have been completed this
summer, Darby said. ``Certainly there's no valid basis for making a
judgment about an undercount or overcount at this point.''
   More than 6,000 local governments - including the nation's 51
largest cities - filed challenges against preliminary figures with
the Census Bureau. The resolution of those local challenges will
help determine the final census totals.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, under whose direction the
Census Bureau operates, has until July 15 to decide whether to add
people that the local officials say were not counted.
   Ralph Munro, secretary of state of Washington state, expressed
concern that eastern cities challenging the census results might
prevail.
   ``We're thinking of intervening on the other side to argue that
the numbers should stand,'' he said.
   New York City Mayor David N. Dinkins said he was ``mad as hell''
with the census figures.
   ``We will fight it to the hilt, because it means to us about a
billion dollars over 10 years and of course a loss of
representation, which is tremendously important,'' he said.
</TEXT>
