<HL>
   Population Shift to Cities
   Accelerated in the 1980s
</HL>
<DATE>
12/18/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<RE>
NORTH CAROLINA (NC)
NORTH DAKOTA (ND)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. population shift from rural to
urban areas accelerated sharply during the 1980s, according
to newly released figures from the 1990 census.
   The change reflects a significant slowdown in rural growth
during the 1980s, and also a small increase in the rate of
urban growth during that decade. The nation's rural
population grew a mere 4% during the 1980s, following a brisk
11% rise in the 1970s. The urban population, which includes
people in cities and surrounding suburbs, grew 12% in the
1980s after increasing 11.6% in the 1970s.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Census Bureau demographer Larry Long said changing
relocation practices of U.S. companies may help explain the
slowdown in rural population growth during the 1980s. Many
companies moved plants from urban to rural areas during the
1970s in an attempt to reduce labor costs, but after the
recession of the early 1980s, such companies were more likely
to relocate plants overseas, he explained.
   Urban dwellers totaled 187 million in 1990, or 75% of the
total population, up from the 1980 tally of 167 million, or
74% of the population, according to the Census Bureau. To a
great extent, this growth reflects a rising number of
immigrants, especially Hispanics and Asians. Immigrants are
much more likely than other groups to live in urban areas.
   In two states, North Carolina and North Dakota,
populations that previously were predominantly rural became
majority urban during the 1980s.
</TEXT>
