<HEAD>Ravaged Area Began as Rail Stop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Flash Floods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHADYSIDE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folklore holds that this village along
the Ohio River got its name from railroad conductors who suggested
that passengers get off on the shady side of the tracks.
   A pamphlet found in a library says James Leasure planted
evergreens along the road to his farm and hung a sign reading
``Shady Side'' at his gate opposite the railroad platform in the
1870s.
   ``Eventually it became known as the Shadyside stop,'' said
Belmont County coroner's investigator Chuck Vogt. ``It's just a
nice, middle-class America town.''
   But it's also a town that has seen hard times, even before last
week's flash flooding killed at least 21 people and left 13 missing.
   The southeastern Ohio county lies in the coal and steel country
of the Appalachian foothills. Its heavily wooded hills are dotted
with bedroom and retirement communities for the mills and mines of
Wheeling, W.Va., and western Pennsylvania.
   ``Because of the closing of many, many coal mines and the
reduction and closing of some steel mills, the population has been
declining,'' said Martins Ferry Library Director John W.P. Storck.
``The average age in Belmont County is increasing, too.''
   Figures from the 1980 census show Belmont County's population
grew from 80,917 in 1970 to 82,569 in 1980, but the figures are
still below the 1940 peak of 95,614.
   Figures from the 1990 census are not yet available, but are
expected to reflect a further decline, Storck said.
   Shadyside, classified as a city until the 1980 census, had to be
reincorporated as a village because its population count of 4,300
was 700 below the Ohio cutoff for a city.
   Figures in a 1989 report compiled by Washington-based Woods &amp;
Poole Economics Inc. show the average age of the county's residents
is about 32.7 years, compared with the statewide average of 29.9.
The report predicts the average will increase to 37.4 in 1995 and
41.1 by 2010.
   But there has been little change in the character of Shadyside
residents, said Sandy Wallace, who grew up in Bellaire and reports
on the area for the Martins Ferry Times-Leader.
   Everybody knows everybody else, ``and that's why this flood has
become such a devastating emotional issue,'' she said.
   ``There's this quality of giving and openness, a very close-knit
and neighborly situation,'' she said. ``And that's something that
I've noticed has really come to the fore in the past few days.''
   Donations of food, clothing, technical assistance and labor for
the backbreaking process of debris removal came from all over
southeastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania and northern West Virginia.
   So much clothing was donated that authorities ran out of storage
space.
</TEXT>
